The key insight is that this follows from energy conservation. The trajectory has constant energy, and when velocity is zero, all energy is potential energy. Let me use the `trajectory_energy` lemma and the relationship between kinetic and potential energy.

```lean
@[sorryful]
lemma trajectory_velocity_eq_zero_iff (IC : InitialConditions) (t : Time)
    (hx : IC.x₀ ≠ 0 ∨ IC.v₀ ≠ 0) :
    ∂ₜ (IC.trajectory S) t = 0 ↔
    ‖(IC.trajectory S) t‖ = √(‖IC.x₀‖^2 + (‖IC.v₀‖/S.ω)^2) := by
  constructor
  · intro hv
    have he := trajectory_energy S IC
    simp [energy, kineticEnergy, potentialEnergy, real_inner_self_eq_norm_sq, hv] at he
    have := he t
    field_simp at this
    rw [sq_eq_sq'] at this
    · exact this.resolve_right (by positivity)
    · positivity
    · apply Real.sqrt_nonneg
  · intro hp
    have he := trajectory_energy S IC
    simp [energy, kineticEnergy, potentialEnergy, real_inner_self_eq_norm_sq] at he
    have := he t
    rw [hp] at this
    field_simp at this
    rw [Real.sq_sqrt (by positivity)] at this
    nlinarith [sq_nonneg (‖∂ₜ (IC.trajectory S) t‖)]
```
